{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503229"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:57:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:57:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1956"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1956"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.36,0.04,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41946"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1956"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26935"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"8936"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40234"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41946"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25 year old woman is brought to the Emergency Department after a suicide attempt involving the consumption of an unidentified substance. Upon arrival, she presents with a reduced level of consciousness and shows signs of impaired coordination. The patient reports experiencing severe abdominal pain, blurry vision and photophobia. Laboratory investigations reveal a high anion gap metabolic acidosis with hyperlactataemia and an elevated osmolar gap.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer urinalysis shows no abnormalities. Her ECG shows no cardiac arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following substances is she most likely to have ingested?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methanol","Ethylene glycol","Isopropanol","Diethylene glycol","Propylene glycol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emethanol poisoning\u003C/strong\u003E, which classically presents with visual impairment (occasionally blindness), reduced GCS, respiratory dysfunction and abdominal pain, followed by the development of delayed neurological sequelae over the subsequent days (or even weeks). Common sources include adulterated spirits, windshield-washer fluid, and various industrial products/fuels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast,\u003Cstrong\u003E ethylene glycol\u003C/strong\u003E (anti-freeze), presents with early neurological dysfunction (particularly cranial nerve deficits) and oxalate crystal deposition resulting in crystalluria and lung/heart/kidney dysfunction. \u003Cstrong\u003EIsopropanol\u003C/strong\u003E, a common ingredient in hand sanitiser, can present with reduced GCS, respiratory dysfunction, acute pancreatitis and cardiovascular collapse. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiethylene glycol,\u003C/strong\u003E most commonly found in brake fluid, presents with gastrointestinal upset, reduced GCS and peripheral neuropathies with progressive liver and kidney dysfunction. In contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Epropylene glycol\u003C/strong\u003E, occasionally used as a \u2018safer\u2019 alternative to ethylene glycol as anti-freeze, is more likely to present with an isolated increased osmolar gap, and only occasionally will feature more serious complications such as a lactic acidosis or acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The rapid onset of severe metabolic acidosis with an elevated anion gap, along with visual disturbances is suggestive of methanol toxicity."],"references":["Kraut JA, Mullins ME, 2018. \u2018Toxic Alcohols\u2019 in New England Journal of Medicine, vol.378, pp 270-280."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26935"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1956"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26935"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-28T11:24:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-03T14:55:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1956"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41946"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synony